To me, the problems with this start from line 1 of the description.



SCP-2294 is a severed, Caucasian hand measuring around fifteen centimeters in length and eight centimeters in width. The hand partially extends beyond its wrist, and the end of the hand is covered in scar tissue and badly damaged in some areas.

The primary anomalous feature of SCP-2294 are the thumb and fingertips of the hand, which have been replaced with heads which strongly resemble the former US president Richard Milhouse Nixon.
附加记录：    

That comma doesn't belong between severed and Caucasian I'm not sure of that. It's a nitpick anyway.
Caucasian is useless as a term to describe what I assume is meant to be its skin tone, as it doesn't tell you anything useful.
What's the use of telling us its size? Or does it infer the size of the penis that goes with it?
The hand partially extends beyond its wrist, and the end of the hand is covered in scar tissue and badly damaged in some areas. - and badly damaged in some areas is confusing. I assume you mean that some areas of the end of the hand (but what end is that exactly?) are badly damaged, instead of being covered in scar tissue. Or are they badly damaged and covered in scar tissue? It's entirely unclear.
Its primary anomalous feature isn't the fingers and thumb, it's the fact that it's a severed hand that somehow isn't decaying.
the former US president - the is superfluous there




Although SCP-2294 is capable of movement through the use of its fingers in a manner similar of certain insects or spiders, it is usually found laying palm up with the fingers raised so that the the instances are facing each other.
附加记录：    

How does that work? It's walking on the faces?
Insects and spiders have a very different limb layout, so to speak. I'd imagine this thing moving around is actually nothing like insects or spiders. But I may be wrong about that


Some of these are nitpicks, others represent a very basic flaw in this article: its execution. Aside from that, there's the fact that it's basically a variation on . I can't help but feel this is retreading old ground, and not in a particularly entertaining way.





